{{update|date=January 2016}} The '''Albert Einstein Peace Prize''' is/was a [[peace prize]] awarded annually since 1980 by the '''Albert Einstein Peace Prize Foundation'''. The Foundation dates from 1979, the centenary of the birth of [[Albert Einstein]], and evokes the [[Russell–Einstein Manifesto]] which urges [[nuclear disarmament]]. It was established, with the sponsorship of the [[trustee]]s of Einstein's [[Estate (law)|estate]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://profiles.nlm.nih.gov/BB/A/P/L/A/_/bbapla.pdf |format=PDF |title=Letter from the Albert Einstein Peace Prize Foundation to Joshua Lederberg |date=14 December 1979 |first=Norman |last=Cousins |authorlink=Norman Cousins |publisher=[[United States National Library of Medicine]] |work=The Joshua Lederberg Papers |accessdate=11 January 2016}}</ref> by William M. Swartz (1912–87) a wealthy businessman and the grandfather of activist [[Aaron Swartz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suntimes.com/business/17594002-420/aaron-swartz-killed-by-government-his-father-says-at-funeral.html|title=Aaron Swartz was ‘killed by government,’ father says at funeral|last=Guy|first=Sandra|date=15 January 2013|work=Sun-Times|accessdate=10 January 2016|location=Chicago|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130118040220/http://www.suntimes.com/business/17594002-420/aaron-swartz-killed-by-government-his-father-says-at-funeral.html|archivedate=18 January 2013}}</ref><ref name="Heise1987">{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1987-11-13/news/8703250765_1_albert-einstein-peace-prize-nuclear-weapons-mr-swartz|title=William Swartz, Peace Agency Founder|last=Heise|first=Kenan|date=November 13, 1987|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=10 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5gUAAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA42|accessdate=10 January 2016|date=January–February 1988|publisher=Educational Foundation for Nuclear Science, Inc.|page=42|title=William M. Swartz, 1912–1987}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Yang|first=Wesley|date=February 8, 2013|title=The Life and Afterlife of Aaron Swartz|journal=New York magazine|url=http://nymag.com/news/features/aaron-swartz-2013-2/index2.html}}</ref> William M. Swartz was involved in the [[Pugwash Conferences on Science and World Affairs]] and established the Foundation in part to support Pugwash.<ref name="basv5n5p2"/> Prize winners, mainly active in nuclear disarmament,<ref>{{cite book|last=Mitchell-Greene|first=Bonnie L.|title=Encyclopedia of Violence, Peace, and Conflict|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=EBzxsURb4-cC&pg=PT4713|date=2008-09-05|publisher=Academic Press|isbn=9780123739858|chapter=Peace Prizes}}</ref> receive(d) $50,000.
